9. me fabulosae. The emphasis on ‘ me ’ points out the connection with the preceding stanzas, ‘no wonder that Ι should hear the Muses' voice, though you do not. I have been their favourite from my baby- hood?

fabulosae, ‘legendary.' ‘De quibus fabulantur poetae.’ They are the birds of Venus that draw her car; they carry ambrosia to Zeus himself (Hom. Od. 12. 62). The suggestion is that their aetion in covering the child-poet in leaves was, like their actions of which legends tell, ‘non sine Dis¹; and, as Conington remarks, the emphatic con- junction ‘me fabulosae,' etc. is as much as to say, ‘ Ι, too, like other poets (as Stesichorus, Pindar, Aeschylus), have a legend of my infancy.’
